and, United Kingdom","Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Poyner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands; of Norman origin): nickname for a fighter, from Anglo-Norman French <i>poigneur</i>, <i>pugneire</i> ‘fighter, warrior’ (from Latin <i>pugnator</i>, from <i>pugnare</i> ‘to fight’, a derivative of <i>pugnus</i> ‘fist’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Poynor","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Leicestershire; of Norman origin): variant of   Poyner  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Poyner of Bedeslow was born in 1423, in Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William Poyner, was 21 and his mother, Jane Harnage, was 12. He married Jane Harnage about 1434, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1445, in his hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1423–1445":"1423–1445","1412–1443":"1412–1443","1443–1462":"1443–1462","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1402":"1402","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1443":"1443","1462":"1462","about 1434":"umbes 1434","Bedeslow, Jarrow, Durham, Eng